It's important to note that `from_utf8_lossy()` creates a new `String` in which invalid UTF-8 bytes are replaced with `U+FFFD REPLACEMENT CHARACTER`. If you want to handle invalid UTF-8 sequences in a more customized way, you can use the `std::str::from_utf8()` method instead, which returns a `Result<String, FromUtf8Error>` and allows you to handle invalid UTF-8 sequences in a more fine-grained manner.
